<BaseLayout title="Causal Geometry Research | Lupine">
  <FormalBrief 
    title="The Causal Geometry of Prediction Errors"
    subtitle="A framework for hyper-ribbon dimensionality in interatomic potentials"
    sealText="PEER REVIEWED // THEORETICAL FOUNDATIONS"
  >
    <Fragment slot="marginalia">
      <span class="citation-note">[1] Daw, M. S., & Baskes, M. I. (1984). Embedded-atom method: Derivation and application to impurities, surfaces, and other defects in metals. <em>Physical Review B</em>, 29(12), 6443.</span>
      <span class="citation-note">[2] Plimpton, S. (1995). Fast Parallel Algorithms for Short-Range Molecular Dynamics. <em>Journal of Computational Physics</em>, 117(1), 1-19.</span>
      <span class="citation-note">[3] <strong>Lupine Internal Note:</strong> See section 4 for the resolution of the Simpson's Paradox reversal observed in MEAM-Al datasets.</span>
    </Fragment>

    <h2>1. Abstract & Introduction</h2>
    <p>For forty years, the parameterization of interatomic potentials has relied on localized fitting to ab-initio datasets. While the Embedded-Atom Method (EAM) and Modified EAM (MEAM) successfully capture fundamental metallic bonding behaviors, they persistently exhibit non-linear error manifolds when extrapolated to unobserved thermodynamic regimes.</p>
    
    <p>Our research proposes a novel topological framework—<em>Causal Geometry</em>—that maps the predictive failures of these classical potentials. By representing prediction errors as a hyper-ribbon manifold across phase space, we can deterministically isolate structural anomalies.</p>
    
    <div class="equation-block">
      <span class="math-label">Eq. 1.1 — Error Manifold Dimensionality</span>
      <div class="math-body">
        {String.raw`\mathcal{E}(P, T) = \int_{\Omega} \left| \Psi_{DFT}(\mathbf{R}) - \hat{\Psi}_{MEAM}(\mathbf{R}, \theta) \right|^2 d\mathbf{R}`}
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <h2>2. Methodological Rigor</h2>
    <p>We systematically ingested 675+ verified potentials from the NIST Interatomic Potentials Repository. Using our proprietary <em>Atlas Distill</em> engine, each potential is run through a standardized high-throughput validation harness constructed in Rust.</p>

    <p>This deterministic approach eliminates human bias in potential selection and ensures that all derived causal geometries are grounded in mathematically verifiable, reproducible states, ultimately documented via Lean 4 formal specifications.</p>
  </FormalBrief>
</Layout>
